#### Similarities

As the Soroban (算盤) originates from the Suanpan (算盤), both share common characteristics, which we list below (<htcite0>):
- Both have a bar that separates the groups of markers;
- The upper markers are called heaven markers and have a value of 5;
- The lower markers are called earth markers and have a value of 1;
- In both, we represent numbers by moving the markers toward the bar.

#### Differences

Upon arriving in Japan (Nippon-koku or Nihon-koku, 日本国), the Soroban (算盤) initially kept the structure imported from China (Zhōngguó, 中國), but gradually underwent transformations, although it preserved the same logic of numerical representation.

The two most visible differences between the abacuses are that, in the Japanese version, first one upper marker was removed, and years later, one lower marker (<htcite1>).
